I'm still not certain whether American Samoa is included in the count, though my understanding is that it is. And there has been a limited spread from the outbreak in neighboring Samoa, with nine cases reported in American Samoa in this latest outbreak. https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-12-08/measles-outbreak-declared-in-samoas-neighbour-american-samoa/11778014 Nonetheless, there's clearly been a aggressive response on both islands, and given the high vaccination rate in the American territory, I have the sense that the spread is being contained. So the nine cases isn't likely to reach the threshold of 224 that would put the overall count for the US over 1,500 for the year. Clearly that's not assured, and my understanding of epidemiology is poor, so I'm going to leave a 1/20 chance at this point that the 1,500 mark will be reached this month.

For a number of reasons we can expect to observe a material slowdown in cases per month. First, measles requires tropical / warm weather to spread and so late Q3 and early Q4 are seasonally the weakest. We can observe this in WHO data (which gives us seasonality by month for a few countries going back many years) - this isn't perfect because some of these countries are in different hemisphere but hopefully it is good enough. Also, 2014 (past peak measles) going into 2015 we saw a 75% drop in cases (simply because of reversion to the mean), so we should expect a slowdown in cases for that reason too. Finally, we are already seeing a slowdown in cases per month because case / month has dropped by about 25 since June. We also get Sep to date data from WHO so you can guess what rest of september will be for purposes of analysis. What worries me is that the rate of slow-down was lower in September (e.g., CDC partial-month number in Sep implies 30 for Sep vs. 24 in Aug), which causes me to expand my bounds upward a bit.

This one was difficult to work through. I took inspiration from dglid's approach and pulled down the WHO measles cases and averaged the individual and cumulative proportions of cases observed for North America, and much of Western Europe. I used this to get a general time trend for the cumulative proportions per month and then worked out an empirical distribution for July cumulative proportions of cases (5th, 50th, and 95th percentiles were .4%, 80%, and ~98%, respectively). I then used the current US cases for the year (1148 as of yesterday) and ran 250 Monte Carlo deviates from the above empiric distribution (ie, 1148/rand-dist). I finally took the logs of these results because of the obvious right skew and used a log normal distribution to calculate the results I posted. My geometric mean came out to be about 1480 with 10th and 90th Percentile values of 1195 and 2016, respectively

Using the CDC website the monthly figures for measles cases were: Jan 52, Feb 154, Mar 181, Apr 317 and May 275. Figure for the week to June 6 was 41. Extrapolating this value then the figure for June would be around 175. From this it looks like the rate of infection is decreasing substantially. Looking at more detail where the outbreaks are, the CDC indicate that ongoing outbreaks (defined as at least 3 people affected) are happening in New York State (2 places), California (3 places), Pennsylvania and Washington state. Looking at figures for these states (from the CDC link to the state health authorities) it seems that the main outbreak in Washington is over, but in May six people were affected in a different part of Washington state which could signify a new outbreak starting. How bad this will be will depend upon how well the outbreak can be contained and whether it hits a large community of unvaccinated people like the New York outbreaks did. I couldn't find much info for Penn state, but New York City's data shows that the rate of infection is tailing off (Jan 34, Feb 69, Mar 160, Apr 177, May 86). New York has had a very aggressive containment policy including mandatory vaccination and this seems to be curtailing spread of the disease and will probably continue to do so, especially if people in neighbouring areas who are unvaccinated decide that the risk is high and they should get vaccinated. The outbreaks in California were much smaller (Jan 4, Feb 2, Mar 14, Apr 21, May 7) but still show the same type of distribution as the NYC and the overall figures, namely that the rate of infection increased significantly in March, increased yet further in April and then decreased noticeably in May. It seems to me that there will most likely be fewer cases in June than in May, and this downward trend may well continue. I heard that spring is the peak time for measles, at least in Europe, and think that it would be similar for the US but haven't fact checked this. If this is the case, then we would expect the number of new cases to tail off significantly over the summer and into early autumn. Having said that, there are usually more people travelling in the summer who could potentially catch measles abroad and bring it back to the US, and the CDC indicated that most of the outbreaks started with people bringing measles into the US from trips abroad. From the data on the 2014 outbreak in the US (thanks cafebedouin for providing the link to the weekly tables) it seems that the number of new cases tails off very rapidly once the infection is past its peak. Assuming that (i) there is no new large NYC style outbreak in an unvaccinated community, and (ii) measles is more prevalent in the spring, then I would expect the total number to be below 1500 by the end of the year.
